---
import NoteBox from "@components/NoteBox.astro";
import Layout from "@layouts/Layout.astro";
import PageHeroVisual from "@components/PageHeroVisual.astro";
import SectionHeading from "@components/SectionHeading.astro";
import SourceLinks from "@components/SourceLinks.astro";
import { PERSON, SITE } from "@data/site";

const title = "Laser Metal Deposition";
const short =
  "Laser Metal Deposition is a metal additive manufacturing route where a focused energy source melts feedstock as it is deposited, often for repair, cladding, local feature addition, and large-part additive manufacturing.";
const description = `${title}: ${short}`;

const faq = [
  ["Is LMD the same as DED?", "LMD is commonly treated as a laser-based Directed Energy Deposition route. DED is the broader process family; LMD is one practical laser-based route within that family."],
  ["Is LMD the same as laser cladding?", "They overlap, but the goal can differ. Laser cladding is often surface or coating focused, while LMD can also include repair, feature addition, and near-net-shape build work."],
  ["Is LMD better than SLM?", "Not universally. LMD often fits larger parts, repair, cladding, and local material addition. SLM/LPBF often fits compact parts, fine detail, and internal channels."],
  ["Does LMD need post-machining?", "Often yes. Many LMD repair or build workflows include machining allowance, tolerance recovery, surface finishing, and inspection after deposition."],
  ["Can LMD be used for repair?", "Yes, repair is one of the common industrial use cases, but feasibility depends on material, damage geometry, access, heat sensitivity, machining allowance, and inspection requirements."]
];

const jsonLd = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "DefinedTerm",
    "@id": `${SITE.canonicalUrl}/glossary/laser-metal-deposition#term`,
    name: title,
    description: short,
    inDefinedTermSet: `${SITE.canonicalUrl}/glossary`
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    mainEntity: faq.map(([question, answer]) => ({
      "@type": "Question",
      name: question,
      acceptedAnswer: { "@type": "Answer", text: answer }
    }))
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "TechArticle",
    headline: `${title} glossary`,
    description,
    author: { "@id": `${SITE.canonicalUrl}/identity#manish-sharma`, name: PERSON.name },
    datePublished: SITE.lastUpdated,
    dateModified: SITE.lastUpdated,
    url: `${SITE.canonicalUrl}/glossary/laser-metal-deposition`
  }
];
---

<Layout title={`${title} - Glossary - Manish Sharma Lab`} description={description} canonical="/glossary/laser-metal-deposition" jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <article class="site-shell py-16 md:py-20">
    <div class="grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,1fr)_minmax(24rem,0.62fr)] lg:items-center">
      <div class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="metric-label">Glossary</p>
        <h1 class="mt-5 text-5xl font-black leading-tight text-white md:text-6xl">{title}</h1>
        <p class="mt-6 text-xl leading-9 text-slate-200">{short}</p>
      </div>
      <PageHeroVisual variant="lmd" class="hidden lg:block" />
    </div>

    <div class="mt-10 grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[0.75fr_1.25fr]">
      <div class="grid h-fit gap-4">
        <NoteBox title="Short answer">LMD adds metal locally with a laser-based deposition process. It is especially relevant when repair, cladding, large parts, or local feature addition matter.</NoteBox>
        <NoteBox title="Common confusion" tone="laser">LMD is not powder-bed SLM/LPBF. LMD feeds material into a melt zone during deposition; SLM/LPBF builds inside a powder bed.</NoteBox>
        <NoteBox title="Buyer/RFQ relevance" tone="steel">A useful LMD RFQ needs material grade, damage or build area, drawings/CAD, photos, tolerances, post-machining expectations, operating conditions, and inspection requirements.</NoteBox>
      </div>
      <div class="prose-lab">
        <h2>Practical Meaning</h2>
        <p>LMD is useful when material needs to be added only where it is needed: a worn region, a local crack repair after material removal, a functional surface, or a feature on a larger component.</p>
        <h2>Technical Context</h2>
        <p>The process depends on heat input, feedstock, shielding, overlap, stand-off distance, path planning, base-material compatibility, and thermal history. These details affect dilution, bonding, geometry, residual stress, and inspection needs.</p>
        <h2>When It Is Used</h2>
        <p>LMD is often considered for industrial repair, laser cladding, hybrid manufacturing, feature addition, large-part builds, and cases where replacement lead time or part value makes local deposition attractive.</p>
        <h2>When It May Not Fit</h2>
        <p>It may not fit when material is unknown, access is poor, heat distortion risk is unacceptable, tolerance cannot be recovered, inspection is impossible, or the part is better suited to powder-bed design freedom.</p>
        <h2>AI and Process-Monitoring Relevance</h2>
        <p>AI can help organize RFQ information, compare process routes, and interpret monitoring signals. It should not turn monitoring data into final quality approval without inspection evidence.</p>
        <h2>Related Terms</h2>
        <p>Related terms include Directed Energy Deposition, DED-LB/M, laser cladding, melt-pool monitoring, RFQ intelligence, post-machining, and inspection evidence.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="mt-14">
      <SectionHeading eyebrow="FAQ" title="Common LMD questions" />
      <div class="mt-8 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
        {faq.map(([question, answer]) => (
          <article class="ordered-card-strong p-5">
            <h2 class="text-lg font-black text-white">{question}</h2>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-300">{answer}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-14 grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[0.85fr_1.15fr]">
      <SectionHeading eyebrow="Source notes" title="Source notes and related pages" description="Do not quote standard wording from this page. Check the original terminology source when exact definitions matter." />
      <div class="grid gap-8">
        <SourceLinks links={[
          { label: "ISO/ASTM additive manufacturing terminology", href: null, status: "Source link to be added", description: "Needed for exact standard wording." },
          { label: "NIST additive manufacturing / DED resources", href: null, status: "Source link to be added", description: "Useful public terminology anchor." },
          { label: "LMD Repairability Index", href: "/frameworks/lmd-repairability-index" },
          { label: "LMD RFQ Toolkit", href: "/agent-pack" },
          { label: "Tools", href: "/tools" },
          { label: "Directed Energy Deposition glossary", href: "/glossary/directed-energy-deposition" }
        ]} />
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>
